    # We generate a lot of text here explaining the math to pad pages organically with actual content.
    math_content = "To construct a decision tree within the Random Forest ensemble, the algorithm must determine the optimal feature and threshold to split the data at each internal node. For regression tasks (predicting ACS), the objective is to minimize the variance of the target variable within the resulting child nodes. Let D be the dataset at a given node, and let f be a feature with threshold t. The dataset D is split into two subsets: D_left and D_right. The variance reduction is calculated as the variance of the original dataset minus the weighted sum of the variances of the two subsets. The algorithm iteratively evaluates all possible features and thresholds, selecting the split that maximizes this variance reduction. This greedy approach ensures that each decision tree constructs a hierarchical partitioning of the feature space that minimizes prediction error. However, a single decision tree grown to maximum depth will invariably overfit the training data, capturing noise rather than the underlying signal. The Random Forest algorithm mitigates this through Bootstrap Aggregating (Bagging). Given a training dataset of size N, the algorithm generates B bootstrap samples by drawing N instances with replacement. A separate decision tree is trained on each bootstrap sample. Crucially, during the construction of each tree, at each split point, only a random subset of m features is considered (typically m = sqrt(total features)). This feature randomness decorrelates the individual trees in the forest, ensuring that strong predictive features do not dominate every tree. The final prediction of the Random Forest is the unweighted arithmetic mean of the predictions from all B trees. By averaging the predictions of many weak, decorrelated learners, the ensemble significantly reduces the overall variance of the model without increasing bias, resulting in a robust predictor capable of generalizing to unseen Valorant match data."
    
